ed into the nation known as the &quot;United States of America&quot;. BTW, there is absolutely nothing in the US Constitution that references a &quot; god &quot; or &quot;christian&quot;, in fact, it specifically states there is to be no religious test of a President or public servant (Article VI) and The People are PROTECTED from the establishment of any religion (First Amendment to Bill of Rights), including christianity . &#10;Sadly, the citizens today have no respect for the very people who secured their freedoms and provided them with the liberty and right to chose their own religion without fear of oppression, that so many around the world dream of. A theocracy looks like Saudi Arabia, and the danger with using terms like &quot; christian nation &quot; is that you could be FORCED to conform to specific set of rules/ laws of a particular christican sect, like cathlocism, angelicism, mormanism, etc. and somehow I don't think you would want that. Be careful what you wish for---it could come back to bite you later on. "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="1299" language="en" documentId="1652" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="LynnS" docType="forumpost" origUrl="http://www.opposingviews.com/questions/should-prayer-be-allowed-in-public-schools#comment-49622" topic="prayer-in-schools" thumbsUp="0" thumbsDown="0" origId="1652" notes="" title="Should Prayer Be Allowed in Public Schools?"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="706"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="43" sofa="1" begin="707" end="1299"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39 43"/></xmi:XMI>